I run it on a 386SX25 with 5MB.  OS/2 will run pretty well in 4MB as long
as you use an alternate shell.  I use PC/2 (freeware) on the 386SX.  Dropping
PM Shell removes about 3 or 4 MB of SOM (system object model) overhead,
while still allowing you to use all the graphical PresentationManager programs.
It has a simple but slick interface that pops up a user-definable program
lauching menu when you double-click on the desktop.  You can also start
PM Shell from PC/2 if you need to use it.

IBM Works (wordpro, spreadsheet, database) and HyperAccess Lite (comm)
are included, as is FaxWorks and the Internet Access Kit.  You can easily
get OS/2 (you probably will want to selectively uninstall some of the
unused OS/2 components and apps--there is a unility included to do this) and
those BonusPack apps in under 100MB, although it's not going
to give you lightning performance in 4MB.  It should be quite usable though
and very stable.

